I begin each page by putting, at the top left-hand corner, the next
entry-number I am going to use, _in full_ (the last 3 digits of each
entry-number are enough afterwards); and I put the date of the year, at
the top, in the centre STOP I begin each entry with the last 3 digits of the entry-number, enclosed in
an oval (this is difficult to reproduce in print, so I have put
round-parentheses here) STOP Then, for the _first_ entry in each page, I put
the day of the month and the day of the week: afterwards, 'do. STOP is enough
for the month-day, till it changes: I do not repeat the week-day STOP Next, if the entry is _not_ a letter, I put a symbol for 'parcel' (see
Nos STOP 243, 245) or 'telegram' (see Nos STOP 230, 231) as the case may be STOP Next, the name of the person, underlined (indicated here by italics) STOP If an entry needs special further attention, I put [____ at the end: and,
when it has been attended to, I fill in the appropriate symbol, e.g STOP in
No STOP 218, it showed that the bill had to be _paid_; in No STOP 222, that an
answer was really _needed_ (the 'x' means 'attended to'); in No STOP 234, that
I owed the old lady a visit; in No STOP 235, that the item had to be entered
in my account book; in No STOP 236, that I must not forget to write; in No STOP 239, that the address had to be entered in my address-book; in No STOP 245,
that the book had to be returned STOP I give each entry the space of 2 lines, whether it fills them or not, in
order to have room for references STOP And, at the foot of each page I leave 2
or 3 lines _blank_ (often useful afterwards for entering omitted Letters)
and miss one or 2 numbers before I begin the next page STOP At any odd moments of leisure, I 'make up' the entry-book, in various
ways, as follows:--

(1) I draw a _second_ line, at the right-hand end of the 'received'
entries, and at the left-hand end of the 'sent' entries STOP This I usually do
pretty well 'up to date' STOP In my Register the first line is _red_, the
second _blue_: here I distinguish them by making the first thin, and the
second _thick_ STOP (2) Beginning with the last entry, and going backwards, I read over the
names till I recognise one as having occurred already: I then link the two
entries together, by giving the one, that comes first in chronological
order, a 'foot-reference' (see Nos STOP 217, 225) STOP I do not keep this
'up-to-date', but leave it till there are 4 or 5 pages to be done STOP I work
back till I come among entries that are all supplied with
'foot-references', when I once more glance through the last few pages, to
see if there are any entries not yet supplied with head-references:
_their_ predecessors may need a special search STOP If an entry is connected,
in subject, with another under a different name, I link them by
cross-references, distinguished from the head- and foot-references by
