Sec STOP 4 STOP _Method of proceeding with a given Pair of Propositions._

Let us suppose that we have before us a Pair of Propositions of
Relation, which contain between them a Pair of codivisional Classes, and
that we wish to ascertain what Conclusion, if any, is consequent from
them STOP We translate them, if necessary, into subscript-form, and then
proceed as follows:--

(1) We examine their Subscripts, in order to see whether they are

    (a) a Pair of Nullities;
    or (b) a Nullity and an Entity;
    or (c) a Pair of Entities STOP (2) If they are a Pair of Nullities, we examine their Eliminands, in
order to see whether they are Unlike or Like STOP If their Eliminands are _Unlike_, it is a case of Fig STOP I STOP We then
examine their Retinends, to see whether one or both of them are asserted
to _exist_ STOP If one Retinend is so asserted, it is a case of Fig STOP I (a);
if both, it is a case of Fig STOP I (b) STOP If their Eliminands are Like, we examine them, in order to see whether
either of them is asserted to exist STOP If so, it is a case of Fig STOP III STOP ;
if not, it is a case of "Fallacy of Like Eliminands not asserted to
exist. STOP (3) If they are a Nullity and an Entity, we examine their Eliminands, in
order to see whether they are Like or Unlike STOP If their Eliminands are Like, it is a case of Fig STOP II STOP ; if _Unlike_, it
is a case of "Fallacy of Unlike Eliminands with an Entity-Premiss. STOP (4) If they are a Pair of Entities, it is a case of "Fallacy of two
Entity-Premisses. STOP [Work Examples Sec STOP =4=, 1-11 (p. 100); Sec STOP =5=, 1-12 (p. 101);
    Sec STOP =6=, 7-12 (p. 106); Sec STOP =7=, 7-12 (p STOP 108). STOP pg085


BOOK VII STOP SORITESES STOP  STOP _INTRODUCTORY._


When a Set of three or more Biliteral Propositions are such that all
their Terms are Species of the same Genus, and are also so related that
two of them, taken together, yield a Conclusion, which, taken with
another of them, yields another Conclusion, and so on, until all have
been taken, it is evident that, if the original Set were true, the last
Conclusion would _also_ be true STOP Such a Set, with the last Conclusion tacked on, is called a '=Sorites=';
the original Set of Propositions is called its '=Premisses='; each of
the intermediate Conclusions is called a '=Partial Conclusion=' of the
Sorites; the last Conclusion is called its '=Complete Conclusion=,' or,
more briefly, its '=Conclusion='; the Genus, of which all the Terms are
Species, is called its '=Universe of Discourse=', or, more briefly, its
'=Univ.='; the Terms, used as Eliminands in the Syllogisms, are called
its '=Eliminands='; and the two Terms, which are retained, and therefore
appear in the Conclusion, are called its '=Retinends=' STOP [Note that each _Partial_ Conclusion contains one or two
    _Eliminands_; but that the _Complete_ Conclusion contains
    _Retinends_ only. STOP The Conclusion is said to be '=consequent=' from the Premisses; for
which reason it is usual to prefix to it the word "Therefore" (or the
symbol ".'.") STOP [Note that the question, whether the Conclusion is or is not
    _consequent_ from the Premisses, is not affected by the _actual_
    truth or falsity of any one of the Propositions which make up
    the Sorites, by depends entirely on their _relationship to one
    another_ STOP pg086
    As a specimen-Sorites, let us take the following Set of 5
    Propositions:--

        (1) "No a are b';
        (2)  All b are c;
        (3)  All c are d;
        (4)  No e' are a';
        (5)  All h are e'" STOP Here the first and second, taken together, yield "No a are c'" STOP This, taken along with the third, yields "No a are d'" STOP This, taken along with the fourth, yields "No d' are e'" STOP And this, taken along with the fifth, yields "All h are d" STOP Hence, if the original Set were true, this would _also_ be true STOP Hence the original Set, with this tacked on, is a _Sorites_; the
    original Set is its _Premisses_; the Proposition "All h are d"
    is its _Conclusion_; the Terms a, b, c, e are its _Eliminands_;
    and the Terms d and h are its _Retinends_ STOP Hence we may write the whole Sorites thus:--

        "No a are b';
         All b are c;
         All c are d;
         No e' are a';
         All h are e' STOP .' STOP All h are d" STOP In the above Sorites, the 3 Partial Conclusions are the
    Positions "No a are e'", "No a are d'", "No d' are e'"; but, if
    the Premisses were arranged in other ways, other Partial
    Conclusions might be obtained STOP Thus, the order 41523 yields the
    Partial Conclusions "No c' are b'", "All h are b", "All h are
    c" STOP There are altogether _nine_ Partial Conclusions to this
    Sorites, which the Reader will find it an interesting task to
    make out for himself. STOP pg087

