Symbolic Method _is_, and in what respects it differs from the many
other Methods already published STOP These matters are as follows:--

    The "Existential Import" of Propositions STOP The use of "is-not" (or "are-not") as a Copula STOP The theory "two Negative Premisses prove nothing. STOP Euler's Method of Diagrams STOP Venn's Method of Diagrams STOP My Method of Diagrams STOP The Solution of a Syllogism by various Methods STOP My Method of treating Syllogisms and Sorites STOP Some account of Parts II, III STOP Sec STOP 2 STOP _The "Existential Import" of Propositions._


The writers, and editors, of the Logical text-books which run in the
ordinary grooves----to whom I shall hereafter refer by the (I hope
inoffensive) title "The Logicians"----take, on this subject, what seems
to me to be a more humble position than is at all necessary STOP They speak
of the Copula of a Proposition "with bated breath", almost as if it were
a living, conscious Entity, capable of declaring for itself what it
chose to mean, and that we, poor human creatures, had nothing to do but
to ascertain _what_ was its sovereign will and pleasure, and submit to
it STOP pg166
In opposition to this view, I maintain that any writer of a book is
fully authorised in attaching any meaning he likes to any word or phrase
he intends to use STOP If I find an author saying, at the beginning of his
book, "Let it be understood that by the word '_black_' I shall always
mean '_white_', and that by the word '_white_' I shall always mean
'_black_'," I meekly accept his ruling, however injudicious I may think
it STOP And so, with regard to the question whether a Proposition is or is not
to be understood as asserting the existence of its Subject, I maintain
that every writer may adopt his own rule, provided of course that it is
consistent with itself and with the accepted facts of Logic STOP Let us consider certain views that may _logically_ be held, and thus
settle which of them may _conveniently_ be held; after which I shall
hold myself free to declare which of them _I_ intend to hold STOP The _kinds_ of Propositions, to be considered, are those that begin with
"some", with "no", and with "all" STOP These are usually called Propositions
"in _I_", "in _E_", and "in _A_" STOP First, then, a Proposition in _I_ may be understood as asserting, or
else as _not_ asserting, the existence of its Subject STOP (By "existence" I
mean of course whatever kind of existence suits its nature STOP The two
Propositions, "_dreams_ exist" and "_drums_ exist", denote two totally
different kinds of "existence" STOP A _dream_ is an aggregate of ideas, and
exists only in the _mind of a dreamer_: whereas a _drum_ is an aggregate
of wood and parchment, and exists in _the hands of a drummer_. STOP First, let us suppose that _I_ "asserts" (i.e STOP "asserts the existence of
its Subject") STOP Here, of course, we must regard a Proposition in _A_ as making the
_same_ assertion, since it necessarily _contains_ a Proposition in _I_ STOP We now have _I_ and _A_ "asserting" STOP Does this leave us free to make
what supposition we choose as to _E_ STOP My answer is "No STOP We are tied down
to the supposition that _E_ does _not_ assert. STOP This can be proved as
follows:--

If possible, let _E_ "assert" STOP Then (taking x, y, and z to represent
Attributes) we see that, if the Proposition "No xy are z" be true, some
things exist with the Attributes x and y: i.e STOP "Some x are y. STOP pg167
Also we know that, if the Proposition "Some xy are z" be true, the same
result follows STOP But these two Propositions are Contradictories, so that one or other of
them _must_ be true STOP Hence this result is _always_ true: i.e STOP the
Proposition "Some x are y" is _always_ true STOP _Quod est absurdum._ (See Note (A), p. 195) STOP We see, then, that the supposition "_I_ asserts" necessarily leads to
"_A_ asserts, but _E_ does not" STOP And this is the _first_ of the various
views that may conceivably be held STOP Next, let us suppose that _I_ does _not_ "assert. STOP And, along with this,
