1 STOP Elementary STOP 1 STOP Whatever can be "attributed to", that is "said to belong to",
a Thing, is called an 'Attribute' STOP For example, "baked", which
can (frequently) be attributed to "Buns", and "beautiful", which
can (seldom) be attributed to "Babies" STOP 2 STOP When they are the Names of two Things (for example, "these
Pigs are fat Animals"), or of two Attributes (for example, "pink
is light red") STOP 3 STOP When one is the Name of a Thing, and the other the Name of an
Attribute (for example, "these Pigs are pink"), since a Thing cannot
actually BE an Attribute STOP 4 STOP That the Substantive shall be supposed to be repeated at the
end of the sentence (for example, "these Pigs are pink (Pigs)") STOP 5 STOP A 'Proposition' is a sentence stating that some, or none, or all,
of the Things belonging to a certain class, called the 'Subject',
are also Things belonging to a certain other class, called the
'Predicate' STOP For example, "some new Cakes are not nice", that is
(written in full) "some new Cakes are not nice Cakes"; where the
class "new Cakes" is the Subject, and the class "not-nice Cakes"
is the Predicate STOP 6 STOP A Proposition, stating that SOME of the Things belonging to
its Subject are so-and-so, is called 'Particular' STOP For example,
"some new Cakes are nice", "some new Cakes are not nice. STOP A Proposition, stating that NONE of the Things belonging to its
Subject, or that ALL of them, are so-and-so, is called 'Universal' STOP For example, "no new Cakes are nice", "all new Cakes are not nice" STOP 7 STOP The Things in each compartment possess TWO Attributes, whose
symbols will be found written on two of the EDGES of that compartment STOP 8 STOP "One or more. STOP 9 STOP As a name of the class of Things to which the whole Diagram is
assigned STOP 10 STOP A Proposition containing two statements STOP For example, "some
new Cakes are nice and some are not-nice. STOP 11 STOP When the whole class, thus divided, is "exhausted" among the
sets into which it is divided, there being no member of it which
does not belong to some one of them STOP For example, the class "new
Cakes" is "exhaustively" divided into "nice" and "not-nice" since
EVERY new Cake must be one or the other STOP 12 STOP When a man cannot make up his mind which of two parties he
will join, he is said to be "sitting on the fence"--not being able
to decide on which side he will jump down STOP 13 STOP "Some x are y" and "no x are y'" STOP 14 STOP A Proposition, whose Subject is a single Thing, is called
